{"title_page": "Morrissey College of Arts & Sciences", "text_new": "{{multiple issues |\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2017}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name           = Boston College <br> Morrissey College of Arts & Sciences (MCAS)\n|image_name     = \n|image_size     = \n|caption        = \n|established    = 1863\n|type           = [[Private school|Private]]\n|dean           = Fr. Gregory Kalscheur, S.J.\n|city           = [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts|Chestnut Hill]]\n|state          = [[Massachusetts]]\n|country        = [[United States]]\n|undergrad      =  6,097\n|postgrad       =  732\n|faculty        = 513\n|campus         = [[Suburban area|Suburban]]\n|website        = {{URL|https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas.html}}\n}}\n\n'''Morrissey College of Arts & Sciences''' (MCAS) is the oldest and largest constituent college of [[Boston College]], situated on the university's main campus in [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts|Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts]]. Founded in 1863, it offers undergraduate and graduate programs in the humanities, social science and natural sciences. \n\nIn the tradition of liberal arts education, the college offers 37 different interdisciplinary programs leading to bachelor's, master's and doctoral degrees. Enrollment includes more than 6,000 undergraduate and nearly 800 graduate students.<ref>https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas.html</ref>\n\n[[File:OldBClithograph.jpg|thumb|left|Early BC in [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston's]] South End]]\n\nIn 2015, the School of Arts & Sciences and Graduate School of Arts & Sciences were renamed in honor of benefactor and alumnus Robert J. Morrissey, class of 1960. Stokes Hall, a humanities building that houses several arts and sciences departments, was completed in 2013.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/03/11/name-college-arts-and-sciences-after-donor-morrissey/9mhi6E4vivrHxDuVSzuG5L/story.html</ref>\n\nMorrissey College has produced many distinguished alumni, including renowned scholars, high-ranking politicians and influential business leaders. It is consistently ranked among the best national and [[Roman Catholic]] ([[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]]) colleges, alongside [[Georgetown College (Georgetown University)|Georgetown College]] and [[Notre Dame College of Arts and Letters| Notre Dame College of Arts and Letters]], in the United States.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-10-catholic-colleges-and-universities-in-the-u-s-1483552525</ref><ref>https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/a12236677/best-catholic-colleges/</ref><ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-colleges/slideshows/explore-the-highest-ranked-catholic-national-universities</ref>\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas.html College of Arts and Sciences Main Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morrissey College of Arts and Sciences}}\n[[Category:Boston College]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues |\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2017}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name           = Boston College <br> Morrissey College of Arts & Sciences (MCAS)\n|image_name     = \n|image_size     = \n|caption        = \n|established    = 1863\n|type           = [[Private school|Private]]\n|dean           = Fr. Gregory Kalscheur, S.J.\n|city           = [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts|Chestnut Hill]]\n|state          = [[Massachusetts]]\n|country        = [[United States]]\n|undergrad      =  6,097\n|postgrad       =  732\n|faculty        = 513\n|campus         = [[Suburban area|Suburban]]\n|website        = {{URL|https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas.html}}\n}}\n\n'''Morrissey College of Arts & Sciences''' (MCAS) is the oldest and largest constituent college of [[Boston College]], situated on the university's main campus in [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts|Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts]]. Founded in 1863, it offers undergraduate and graduate programs in the humanities, social science and natural sciences. \n\nIn the tradition of liberal arts education, the college offers 37 different interdisciplinary programs leading to bachelor's, master's and doctoral degrees. Enrollment includes more than 6,000 undergraduate and nearly 800 graduate students.<ref>https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas.html</ref>\n\n[[File:OldBClithograph.jpg|thumb|left|Early BC in [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston's]] South End]]\n\nIn 2015, the College of Arts & Sciences was renamed in honor of benefactor and alumnus Robert J. Morrissey, class of 1960. Stokes Hall, a humanities building that houses several arts and sciences departments, was completed in 2013.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/03/11/name-college-arts-and-sciences-after-donor-morrissey/9mhi6E4vivrHxDuVSzuG5L/story.html</ref>\n\nMorrissey College has produced many distinguished alumni, including renowned scholars, high-ranking politicians and influential business leaders. It is consistently ranked among the best national and [[Roman Catholic]] ([[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]]) colleges, alongside [[Georgetown College (Georgetown University)|Georgetown College]] and [[Notre Dame College of Arts and Letters| Notre Dame College of Arts and Letters]], in the United States.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-10-catholic-colleges-and-universities-in-the-u-s-1483552525</ref><ref>https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/a12236677/best-catholic-colleges/</ref><ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-colleges/slideshows/explore-the-highest-ranked-catholic-national-universities</ref>\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas.html College of Arts and Sciences Main Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morrissey College of Arts and Sciences}}\n[[Category:Boston College]]\n", "name_user": "BCLicious", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morrissey_College_of_Arts_%26_Sciences"}
